Classification Tree Approach¶

Here, I apply a classification tree approach to this dataset instead of logistic regression. We first import and process the data in a similar way as we did before. m

Some of the age data is missing. What to do about this? Let's get rid of this at first and just see if we can get our classifier going.

Imputation of Missing Age Values¶

The model doesn't know what to do with the NaN values in AGE. Let's make a submodel that is a linear regression predicting AGE from Fare and Class (and embark location while we're at it). We can use this to impute Ages for the ones that are missing.

#OK Let's try a cross-validation strategy here using scikit-learn
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

kf = KFold(n_splits=5)
for train, test in kf.split(X):
    clf2.fit(X.loc[train],Y.loc[train])
    yPred = clf2.predict(X.loc[test])
    cmat = confusion_matrix(Y.loc[test],yPred)
    accuracy = np.trace(cmat)/np.sum(cmat)
    print("Accuracy for test was %2.2f" % accuracy)

OK. It looks like our tree is a bit complicated. We need to prune it back to prevent overfitting. m

In [66]:
clf2 =  tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=3, min_samples_leaf=5)
clf2.fit(X,Y)

kf = KFold(n_splits=5)
mean_accuracy = 0
for train, test in kf.split(X):
    clf2.fit(X.loc[train],Y.loc[train])
    yPred = clf2.predict(X.loc[test])
    cmat = confusion_matrix(Y.loc[test],yPred)
    accuracy = np.trace(cmat)/np.sum(cmat)
    mean_accuracy += accuracy/5
    print("Accuracy for test was %2.2f" % accuracy)
    
print("Mean cross-validation accuracy was %2.2f" % mean_accuracy)    
dot_data = StringIO()

export_graphviz(clf2, out_file=dot_data,  
                filled=True, rounded=True,
                special_characters=True)

CART Result¶

This scored a 78.9% on the website, which was a bit better than my logistic regression result! Interestingly, this is closs to our cross-validation result which suggests that reducing maxdepth dealt well with overfit. Now, let's see if using a Random Forest can do even better.

In [95]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators = 1000, criterion = "entropy", max_depth=2, max_leaf_nodes=5)

kf = KFold(n_splits=5)
mean_accuracy = 0

for train, test in kf.split(X):
    rf.fit(X.loc[train],Y.loc[train,"Survived"])
    yPred = rf.predict(X.loc[test])
    cmat = confusion_matrix(Y.loc[test],yPred)
    accuracy = np.trace(cmat)/np.sum(cmat)
    mean_accuracy += accuracy/5
    print("Accuracy for test was %2.2f" % accuracy)
    
print("Mean cross-validation accuracy was %2.2f" % mean_accuracy) 
    

Accuracy for test was 0.78
Accuracy for test was 0.79
Accuracy for test was 0.83
Accuracy for test was 0.76
Accuracy for test was 0.83
Mean cross-validation accuracy was 0.80

This seemed to put out the same range of using the cross-validation accuracy as the simple CART model, even after playing with the parameters. Depth=2 seemed to also produc around 80% cross-validation accuracy, so I went with that value, again to fight overfit.

Random Forest Result¶

The random forest model with depth=2 did worse than the single classification tree (77.5% accuracy). Change the depth back to 3 didn't seem to affect the result of the random forest prediction and had the same accuracy. Increasing depth to 5 reduced accuracy to 77%, which suggests more overfitting.
